President Barack Obama will award the Medal of Honor to Army Command Sergeant Major Bennie G. Adkins and Army Specialist Four Donald P. Sloat for their courageous actions during combat operations. Command Sergeant Major Adkins served as an Intelligence Sergeant assigned to Detachment A-102, 5th Special Forces Group, 1st Special Forces. He distinguished himself during combat operations in Vietnam in 1966. Specialist Four Donald P. Sloat served as a Machine gunner with Company D, 2nd Battalion, 1st Infantry Regiment, 196th Light Infantry Brigade, Americal Division. He distinguished himself during combat operations in Vietnam in 1970. Command Sergeant Major Adkins joined the Army in 1956 and served in Vietnam three times. He retired from the Army in 1978. Specialist Four Sloat was killed in action in 1970 at the age of 20. The Medal of Honor is awarded to members of the Armed Forces who display extraordinary bravery or self-sacrifice in the face of great risk.